  "prompt": "Is money laundering unlawful?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is unlawful in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to make the money appear as though it comes from a legitimate source.\n\nLaw enforcement agencies and regulatory bodies have established various measures and laws to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities. These measures often include stringent reporting requirements for financial institutions, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations, and international cooperation through organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF).\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. The exact legal framework and penalties vary by country, but the act of money laundering is universally considered a serious crime.",
